mkring 1256","before 1291":"før 1291","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"about 1245–before 1311":"circa 1245–vóór 1311","1193–Female":"1193–Overleden","1240–1281":"1240–1281","1243–1311":"1243–1311","1245–1311":"1245–1311","–Male":"Overleden","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1225–1273":"1225–1273","–Female":"Overleden","before 3 May 1275":"vóór 3 mei 1275","before 1311":"vóór 1311","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1281":"1281","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1256":"1256","1245":"1245","1311":"1311","1243":"1243","about 1245":"circa 1245","about 1256":"circa 1256","before 1291":"vóór 1291","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1245–before 1311":"about 1245–before 1311","1193–Female":"1193–Deceased","1240–1281":"1240–1281","1243–1311":"1243–1311","1245–1311":"1245–1311","–Male":"Deceased","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1225–1273":"1225–1273","–Female":"Deceased","before 3 May 1275":"before 3 May 1275","before 1311":"before 1311","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1281":"1281","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1256":"1256","1245":"1245","1311":"1311","1243":"1243","about 1245":"about 1245","about 1256":"about 1256","before 1291":"before 1291","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Wark, Northumberland, England":"Wark, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bertram","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English (mainly in southeastern Scotland, of Norman origin), French, and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bertram</i>, composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. The raven was the bird of Odin, king of the gods, in ancient Germanic mythology. The personal name was common in France throughout the Middle Ages (especially in the form   Bertrand  ), where its popularity was increased by the fame of the troubadour Bertrand de Born (<i>c.</i> 1140–1214). The name was taken to England by the Normans in the forms <i>Bertran(d)</i>, <i>Bertram</i>, and <i>Bartram</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Beltrami","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dante, Dino, Marco, Pio, Sal, Tullio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Beltrame</i>, from an ancient Germanic name composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bartram","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and North German: variant of   Bertram  .","History: William Bartram, a Quaker, had a large farm near Darby, PA, when his eldest son, John, the first American botanist, was born in 1699. John conducted botanical experiments at his own farm in Kingsessing, PA, near Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Bertman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Wilhelm.","Americanized form of German <b>Bertmann</b>: altered form (by folk etymology) of   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bethke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Eldor, Ewald, Otto, Rudi, Wilhelmina.","North German: from a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal names   Bertram   or   Berthold  . See also   Beth  ."]},{"name":"Bertrand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Monique, Francois, Gilles, Raoul, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Odette.","French, Walloon, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Bertrand</i>, a variant of   Bertram  , coined by folk etymology under the influence of the present participle endings <i>-and</i>, <i>-ant</i>.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Beltran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Luis, Pedro, Jorge, Mario, Ricardo, Francisco, Rafael.","Spanish (<b>Beltrán</b>), Catalan, and southern French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Beltramo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo.","Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Beltramo</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Bertram  )."]},{"name":"Bert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philibert, Pierre.","German, French, and Polish: from a short form of various compound personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ (see for example   Bertram  ).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Berte</i> (Old French <i>Berte</i>, from ancient Germanic   Berta  )."]},{"name":"Battermann","meanings":["German:","possibly an occupational name for a merchant or peddler, from <i>Bartermann</i>.","alternatively, perhaps from a short form of the personal name   Bertram   + Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Bertran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jorge, Eduardo, Enrique, Joaquin, Ricardo, Aleida, Ana, Ana Maria, Elena, Felipe, Jeronimo.  French Andre.","French, Occitan, and Catalan: variant of   Bertram   or   Bertrand  ."]}]},{"name":"Christian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Christianus</i> ‘follower of Christ’, in use as a given name from the Middle Ages onwards, especially as a girl's name. The name of <i>Christ</i> (Greek <i>Khristos</i>) is a translation of the Hebrew term <i>Messiah</i> ‘anointed’."],"variants":[{"name":"Christianne","meanings":["From Latin <i>Christianus</i> ‘follower of Christ’, in use as a given name from the Middle Ages onwards, especially as a girl's name. The name of <i>Christ</i> (Greek <i>Khristos</i>) is a translation of the Hebrew term <i>Messiah</i> ‘anointed’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Christian Bertram was born about 1245, in Mitford, Northumberland, England as the daughter of Roger Bertram and Joan. She married Robert Penulbury before 1291. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died before 1311."},"et":{"about 1245–before 1311":"umbes 1245–enne 1311","1193–Female":"1193–Surnud","1240–1281":"1240–1281","1243–1311":"1243–1311","1245–1311":"1245–1311","–Male":"Surnud","1228–1275":"1228–1275","1256–1296":"1256–1296","1225–1273":"1225–1273","–Female":"Surnud","before 3 May 1275":"enne 3. maid 1275","before 1311":"enne 1311","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1281":"1281","1193":"1193","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1256":"1256","1245":"1245","1311":"1311","1243":"1243","about 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1256":"umbe